b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Study presented at ESC 2026 congress"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Neurofilament light chain linked to cognitive outcomes"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Research stage, not yet clinical practice"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["For survivors of out-of-hospital cardiac arrest, one of the most difficult questions has long been: will cognitive function return? A study presented this week at ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://medicalxpress.com","children":"ESC Acute CardioVascular Care 2026"}]," suggests a possible answer may lie in a simple blood test. Researchers found that early measurement of neurofilament light chain (NfL) — a protein released when nerve cells are damaged — could help predict which patients are at higher risk of cognitive impairment following cardiac arrest.\nThe findings, presented at the annual congress of the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.escardio.org","children":"Association for Acute CardioVascular Care"}],", represent an observational study. This is critical context: the research identifies a correlation, not yet a proven clinical tool. Sample size and methodology details remain to be fully scrutinized through peer review. What we have is a promising signal — but the distance between a conference presentation and validated clinical protocol is substantial."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/blood-marker-shows-promise-predicting-post-arrest-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the evidence shows — and what it doesn't","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"What the evidence shows — and what it doesn't"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["What does this mean for patients today? In practical terms, not much has changed yet. NfL measurement is not currently part of standard post-arrest care, and clinicians cannot act on these findings until they're validated through larger trials and regulatory review.\nWhat we don't know remains significant. We don't yet understand how NfL levels interact with other factors — age, arrest duration, intervention timing. We don't know whether early identification of cognitive risk would change patient outcomes, or simply provide information. And we don't have regulatory clearance for this specific application of NfL testing. According to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://medicalxpress.com","children":"MedicalXpress"}],", the study positions NfL as a novel marker — but novelty and clinical utility are different measures.\nThe study marks a step forward in understanding brain injury after cardiac arrest. But the real measure isn't in laboratory values — it will be in whether this knowledge eventually improves care for the patients who need it most."]}]]}]
